Paulo\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Tel_Aviv" title="Tel Aviv">\n        Tel Aviv\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Warsaw" title="Warsaw">\n        Warsaw\n       </a>\n       .\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       On March 15, 2016, Google announced the introduction of Google Analytics 360 Suite, "a set of integrated data and marketing analytics products, designed specifically for the needs of enterprise-class marketers" which can be integrated with\n       <a href="/wiki/BigQuery" title="BigQuery">\n        BigQuery\n       </a>\n       on the Google Cloud Platform. Among other things, the suite is designed to help "enterprise class marketers" "see the complete customer journey", generate "useful insights", and "deliver engaging experiences to the right people".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-155">\n        <a href="#cite_note-155">\n         [154]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Jack Marshall of\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal" title="The Wall Street Journal">\n         The Wall Street Journal\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       wrote that the suite competes with existing marketing cloud offerings by companies including\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Adobe_Systems" title="Adobe Systems">\n        Adobe\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Oracle_Corporation" title="Oracle Corporation">\n        Oracle\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Salesforce.com" title="Salesforce.com">\n        Salesforce\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">\n        IBM\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-156">\n        <a href="#cite_note-156">\n         [155]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Internet_services">\n        Internet services\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <p>\n       In February 2010, Google announced the\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_Fiber" title="Google Fiber">\n        Google Fiber\n       </a>\n       project, with experimental plans to build an ultra-high-speed broadband network for 50,000 to 500,000 customers in one or more American cities.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-157">\n        <a href="#cite_note-157">\n         [156]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-158">\n        <a href="#cite_note-158">\n         [157]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Following Google\'s corporate restructure to make\n       <a href="/wiki/Alphabet_Inc." title="Alphabet Inc.">\n        Alphabet Inc.\n       </a>\n       its parent company, Google Fiber was moved to Alphabet\'s Access division.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-159">\n        <a href="#cite_note-159">\n         [158]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-160">\n        <a href="#cite_note-160">\n         [159]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In April 2015, Google announced\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Project_Fi" title="Project Fi">\n        Project Fi\n       </a>\n       , a mobile virtual network operator, that combines Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different telecommunication providers in an effort to enable seamless connectivity and fast Internet signal.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-161">\n        <a href="#cite_note-161">\n         [160]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-162">\n        <a href="#cite_note-162">\n         [161]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-163">\n        <a href="#cite_note-163">\n         [162]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In September 2016, Google began its Google Station initiative, a project for public Wi-Fi at railway stations in India. Caesar Sengupta, VP for Google\'s next billion users, told\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/The_Verge" title="The Verge">\n         The Verge\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       that 15,000 people get online for the first time thanks to Google Station and that 3.5 million people use the service every month. The expansion meant that Google was looking for partners around the world to further develop the initiative, which promised "high-quality, secure, easily accessible Wi-Fi".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-164">\n        <a href="#cite_note-164">\n         [163]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       By December, Google Station had been deployed at 100 railway stations,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-165">\n        <a href="#cite_note-165">\n         [164]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and in February, Google announced its intention to expand beyond railway stations, with a plan to bring citywide Wi-Fi to\n       <a href="/wiki/Pune" title="Pune">\n        Pune\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-166">\n        <a href="#cite_note-166">\n         [165]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-167">\n        <a href="#cite_note-167">\n         [166]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Other_products">\n        Other products\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <p>\n       In May 2011, Google announced\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google_Wallet" title="Google Wallet">\n        Google Wallet\n       </a>\n       , a mobile application for wireless payments.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-168">\n        <a href="#cite_note-168">\n         [167]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2013, Google launched\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google_Shopping_Express" title="Google Shopping Express">\n        Google Shopping Express\n       </a>\n       , a delivery service initially available only in San Francisco and Silicon Valley.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-169">\n        <a href="#cite_note-169">\n         [168]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h2>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_affairs">\n        Corporate affairs\n       </span>\n      </h2>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Finance">\n        Finance\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Further information:\n       <a href="/wiki/Corporation_tax_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland#Multinational_tax_schemes" title="Corporation tax in the Republic of Ireland">\n        Corporation tax in the Republic of Ireland \xc2\xa7\xc2\xa0Multinational tax schemes\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_tax" title="Google tax">\n        Google tax\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg">\n         <img alt="Eric Schmidt, Sergey Brin, and Larry Page sitting together" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2217" data-file-width="2916" decoding="async" height="167" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg/220px-Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg/330px-Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg/440px-Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Then-CEO, now Chairman of Google\n         <a href="/wiki/Eric_Schmidt" title="Eric Schmidt">\n          Eric Schmidt\n         </a>\n         with cofounders\n         <a href="/wiki/Sergey_Brin" title="Sergey Brin">\n          Sergey Brin\n         </a>\n         and\n         <a href="/wiki/Larry_Page" title="Larry Page">\n          Larry Page\n         </a>\n         (left to right) in 2008.\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       Google\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/Initial_public_offering" title="Initial public offering">\n        initial public offering\n       </a>\n       (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004. At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-IPO_58-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-IPO-58">\n         [57]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:1_59-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-:1-59">\n         [58]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The sale of $1.67 billion gave Google a\n       <a href="/wiki/Market_capitalization" title="Market capitalization">\n        market capitalization\n       </a>\n       of more than $23 billion.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-washpost_62-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-washpost-62">\n         [61]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The stock performed well after the IPO, with shares hitting $350 for the first time on October 31, 2007,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-170">\n        <a href="#cite_note-170">\n         [169]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       primarily because of strong sales and earnings in the\n       <a href="/wiki/Online_advertising" title="Online advertising">\n        online advertising\n       </a>\n       market.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-bowlingforgoogle_171-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-bowlingforgoogle-171">\n         [170]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The surge in stock price was fueled mainly by individual investors, as opposed to large institutional investors and\n       <a href="/wiki/Mutual_fund" title="Mutual fund">\n        mutual funds\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-bowlingforgoogle_171-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-bowlingforgoogle-171">\n         [170]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       GOOG shares split into GOOG\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Class_C_share" title="Class C share">\n        class C shares\n       </a>\n       and GOOGL\n       <a href="/wiki/Class_A_share" title="Class A share">\n        class A shares\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-172">\n        <a href="#cite_note-172">\n         [171]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The company is listed on the\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/NASDAQ" title="NASDAQ">\n        NASDAQ\n       </a>\n       stock exchange under the\n       <a href="/wiki/Ticker_symbol" title="Ticker symbol">\n        ticker symbols\n       </a>\n       GOOGL and GOOG, and on the\n       <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt_Stock_Exchange" title="Frankfurt Stock Exchange">\n        Frankfurt Stock Exchange\n       </a>\n       under the ticker symbol GGQ1. These ticker symbols now refer to Alphabet Inc., Google\'s holding company, since the fourth quarter of 2015.\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-173">\n        <a href="#cite_note-173">\n         [172]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       The corporation\'s consolidated revenue for the third quarter of 2013 was reported in mid-October 2013 as $14.89 billion, a 12 percent increase compared to the previous quarter.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-174">\n        <a href="#cite_note-174">\n         [173]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google\'s Internet business was responsible for $10.8 billion of this total, with an increase in the number of users\' clicks on advertisements.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-175">\n        <a href="#cite_note-175">\n         [174]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       By January 2014, Google\'s market capitalization had grown to $397 billion.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Marketwatch_176-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-Marketwatch-176">\n         [175]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google uses various\n       <a href="/wiki/Tax_avoidance" title="Tax avoidance">\n        tax avoidance strategies\n       </a>\n       . Out of the\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_the_largest_information_technology_companies" title="List of the largest information technology companies">\n        five largest American technology companies\n       </a>\n       , it pays the lowest taxes to the countries of origin of its revenues. Google between 2007 and 2010 saved $3.1 billion in taxes by shuttling non-U.S. profits through\n       <a href="/wiki/Ireland" title="Ireland">\n        Ireland\n       </a>\n       and the\n       <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">\n        Netherlands\n       </a>\n       and then to\n       <a href="/wiki/Bermuda" title="Bermuda">\n        Bermuda\n       </a>\n       . Such techniques lower its non-U.S. tax rate to 2.3 per cent, while normally the corporate tax rate in for instance the UK is 28 per cent.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-177">\n        <a href="#cite_note-177">\n         [176]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       This has reportedly sparked a French investigation into Google\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/Transfer_pricing" title="Transfer pricing">\n        transfer pricing\n       </a>\n       practices.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-178">\n        <a href="#cite_note-178">\n         [177]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google said it overhauled its controversial global tax structure and consolidated all of its intellectual property holdings back to the US.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GoogleIPRichardWaters_179-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-GoogleIPRichardWaters-179">\n         [178]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google Vice-President\n       <a href="/wiki/Matt_Brittin" title="Matt Brittin">\n        Matt Brittin\n       </a>\n       testified to the\n       <a href="/wiki/Public_Accounts_Committee_(United_Kingdom)" title="Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)">\n        Public Accounts Committee\n       </a>\n       of the UK House of Commons that his UK sales team made no sales and hence owed no sales taxes to the UK.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-180">\n        <a href="#cite_note-180">\n         [179]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In January 2016, Google reached a settlement with the UK to pay \xc2\xa3130m in back taxes plus higher taxes in future.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-181">\n        <a href="#cite_note-181">\n         [180]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2017, Google channeled $22.7 billion from the Netherlands to Bermuda to reduce its tax bill.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-182">\n        <a href="#cite_note-182">\n         [181]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2013, Google ranked 5th in\n       <a href="/wiki/Lobbying_in_the_United_States" title="Lobbying in the United States">\n        lobbying\n       </a>\n       spending, up from 213th in 2003. In 2012, the company ranked 2nd in campaign donations of technology and Internet sections.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-lobby1_183-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-lobby1-183">\n         [182]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Corporate_identity">\n        Corporate identity\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Main articles:\n       <a href="/wiki/History_of_Google#Name" title="History of Google">\n        History of Google \xc2\xa7\xc2\xa0Name\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_(verb)" title="Google (verb)">\n        Google (verb)\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_logo" title="Google logo">\n        Google logo\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_Doodle" title="Google Doodle">\n        Google Doodle\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Google_April_Fools%27_Day_jokes" title="List of Google April Fools\' Day jokes">\n        List of Google April Fools\' Day jokes\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Google_Easter_eggs" title="List of Google Easter eggs">\n        List of Google Easter eggs\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="258" data-file-width="750" decoding="async" height="69" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg/200px-Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg/300px-Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg/400px-Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg.png 2x" width="200"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Logo_Google_2013_Official.svg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Google\'s logo from 2013-2015\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       The name "Google" originated from a misspelling of "\n       <a href="/wiki/Googol" title="Googol">\n        googol\n       </a>\n       ",\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-184">\n        <a href="#cite_note-184">\n         [183]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Hanley_185-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-Hanley-185">\n         [184]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       which refers to the number represented by a 1 followed by one-hundred zeros. Page and Brin write in their original paper on\n       <a href="/wiki/PageRank" title="PageRank">\n        PageRank\n       </a>\n       :\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-originalpaper_30-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-originalpaper-30">\n         [29]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       "We chose our systems name, Google, because it is a common spelling of googol, or 10\n       <sup>\n        100\n       </sup>\n       and fits well with our goal of building very large-scale search engines." Having found its way increasingly into everyday language, the verb "\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_(verb)" title="Google (verb)">\n        google\n       </a>\n       " was added to the\n       <i>\n        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Merriam-Webster_Collegiate_Dictionary" title="Merriam-Webster Collegiate Dictionary">\n         Merriam Webster Collegiate Dictionary\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       and the\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/Oxford_English_Dictionary" title="Oxford English Dictionary">\n         Oxford English Dictionary\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       in 2006, meaning "to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet."\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-186">\n        <a href="#cite_note-186">\n         [185]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-187">\n        <a href="#cite_note-187">\n         [186]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/Mission_statement" title="Mission statement">\n        mission statement\n       </a>\n       , from the outset, was "to organize the world\'s information and make it universally accessible and useful",\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-188">\n        <a href="#cite_note-188">\n         [187]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and its unofficial slogan is "\n       <a href="/wiki/Don%27t_be_evil" title="Don\'t be evil">\n        Don\'t be evil\n       </a>\n       ".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-189">\n        <a href="#cite_note-189">\n         [188]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In October 2015, a related motto was adopted in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase: "Do the right thing".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-190">\n        <a href="#cite_note-190">\n         [189]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The original motto was retained in the code of conduct of Google, now a subsidiary of Alphabet.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:0_17-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-:0-17">\n         [16]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       The original\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_logo" title="Google logo">\n        Google logo\n       </a>\n       was designed by Sergey Brin.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-191">\n        <a href="#cite_note-191">\n         [190]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Since 1998,\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google has been designing special, temporary alternate logos to place on their homepage intended to celebrate holidays, events, achievements and people. The first\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_Doodle" title="Google Doodle">\n        Google Doodle\n       </a>\n       was in honor of the\n       <a href="/wiki/Burning_Man" title="Burning Man">\n        Burning Man Festival\n       </a>\n       of 1998.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-192">\n        <a href="#cite_note-192">\n         [191]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-193">\n        <a href="#cite_note-193">\n         [192]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The doodle was designed by\n       <a href="/wiki/Larry_Page" title="Larry Page">\n        Larry Page\n       </a>\n       and\n       <a href="/wiki/Sergey_Brin" title="Sergey Brin">\n        Sergey Brin\n       </a>\n       to notify users of their absence in case the servers crashed. Subsequent Google Doodles were designed by an outside contractor, until Larry and Sergey asked then-\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Intern" title="Intern">\n        intern\n       </a>\n       <a href="/wiki/Dennis_Hwang" title="Dennis Hwang">\n        Dennis Hwang\n       </a>\n       to design a logo for\n       <a href="/wiki/Bastille_Day" title="Bastille Day">\n        Bastille Day\n       </a>\n       in 2000. From that point onward, Doodles have been organized and created by a team of employees termed "Doodlers".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-194">\n        <a href="#cite_note-194">\n         [193]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google has a tradition of creating\n       <a href="/wiki/April_Fools%27_Day" title="April Fools\' Day">\n        April Fools\' Day\n       </a>\n       jokes. Its first on April 1, 2000 was\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google%27s_hoaxes#2000" title="Google\'s hoaxes">\n        Google MentalPlex\n       </a>\n       which allegedly featured the use of mental power to search the web.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mentalplex_195-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-mentalplex-195">\n         [194]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2007, Google announced a free Internet service called\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/TiSP" title="TiSP">\n        TiSP\n       </a>\n       , or Toilet Internet Service Provider, where one obtained a connection by flushing one end of a\n       <a href="/wiki/Optical_fiber" title="Optical fiber">\n        fiber-optic\n       </a>\n       cable down their toilet.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TiSP_196-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-TiSP-196">\n         [195]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google\'s services contain\n       <a href="/wiki/Easter_egg_(media)" title="Easter egg (media)">\n        easter eggs\n       </a>\n       , such as the\n       <a href="/wiki/Swedish_Chef" title="Swedish Chef">\n        Swedish Chef\n       </a>\n       \'s "Bork bork bork,"\n       <a href="/wiki/Pig_Latin" title="Pig Latin">\n        Pig Latin\n       </a>\n       , "Hacker" or\n       <a href="/wiki/Leet" title="Leet">\n        leetspeak\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Elmer_Fudd" title="Elmer Fudd">\n        Elmer Fudd\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/International_Talk_Like_a_Pirate_Day" title="International Talk Like a Pirate Day">\n        Pirate\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Klingon_language" title="Klingon language">\n        Klingon\n       </a>\n       as language selections for its search engine.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-197">\n        <a href="#cite_note-197">\n         [196]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       When searching for the word "\n       <a href="/wiki/Anagram" title="Anagram">\n        anagram\n       </a>\n       ," meaning a rearrangement of letters from one word to form other valid words, Google\'s suggestion feature displays "Did you mean: nag a ram?"\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-198">\n        <a href="#cite_note-198">\n         [197]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Workplace_culture">\n        Workplace culture\n        <span id="Innovation_Time_Off">\n        </span>\n        <span id="Employees">\n        </span>\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="thumb tleft">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3456" data-file-width="5184" decoding="async" height="147" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png/220px-Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png/330px-Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png/440px-Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Pride_in_London_2016_-_Google_participating_in_the_parade.png" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Google employees marching in the\n         <a href="/wiki/Pride_in_London" title="Pride in London">\n          Pride in London\n         </a>\n         parade in 2016\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       On\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/Fortune_(magazine)" title="Fortune (magazine)">\n         Fortune\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       magazine\'s list of the best companies to work for, Google ranked first in 2007, 2008 and 2012,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-best_company_199-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-best_company-199">\n         [198]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-200">\n        <a href="#cite_note-200">\n         [199]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-201">\n        <a href="#cite_note-201">\n         [200]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and fourth in 2009 and 2010.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-202">\n        <a href="#cite_note-202">\n         [201]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-203">\n        <a href="#cite_note-203">\n         [202]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google was also nominated in 2010 to be the world\'s most attractive employer to graduating students in the Universum Communications talent attraction index.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-204">\n        <a href="#cite_note-204">\n         [203]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google\'s corporate philosophy includes principles such as "you can make money without doing evil," "you can be serious without a suit," and "work should be challenging and the challenge should be fun."\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-205">\n        <a href="#cite_note-205">\n         [204]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       As of December 2018,\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google has 98,771 employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EmployeesAsOf2018Q4_10-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-EmployeesAsOf2018Q4-10">\n         [9]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google\'s 2017\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       diversity report states that 31 percent of its workforce are women and 69 percent are men, with the ethnicity of its workforce being predominantly white (56%) and Asian (35%).\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2017DiversityReport_206-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-2017DiversityReport-206">\n         [205]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Within tech roles, however, 20 percent were women; and 25 percent of leadership roles were held by women.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-2017DiversityReport_206-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-2017DiversityReport-206">\n         [205]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google\'s employees are hired based on a hierarchical system. Employees are split into six hierarchies based on experience and can range "from entry-level data center workers at level one to managers and experienced engineers at level six."\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-207">\n        <a href="#cite_note-207">\n         [206]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       As a motivation technique, Google uses a policy known as\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Innovation_Time_Off" title="Innovation Time Off">\n        Innovation Time Off\n       </a>\n       , where Google engineers are encouraged to spend 20% of their work time on projects that interest them. Some of Google\'s services, such as\n       <a href="/wiki/Gmail" title="Gmail">\n        Gmail\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_News" title="Google News">\n        Google News\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Orkut" title="Orkut">\n        Orkut\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/AdSense" title="AdSense">\n        AdSense\n       </a>\n       originated from these independent endeavors.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-208">\n        <a href="#cite_note-208">\n         [207]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In a talk at Stanford University,\n       <a href="/wiki/Marissa_Mayer" title="Marissa Mayer">\n        Marissa Mayer\n       </a>\n       , Google\'s Vice-President of Search Products and User Experience until July 2012, showed that half of all new product launches in the second half of 2005 had originated from the Innovation Time Off.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-209">\n        <a href="#cite_note-209">\n         [208]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2005, articles in\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">\n         The New York Times\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-210">\n        <a href="#cite_note-210">\n         [209]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and other sources began suggesting that Google had lost its anti-corporate, no evil philosophy.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-211">\n        <a href="#cite_note-211">\n         [210]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-212">\n        <a href="#cite_note-212">\n         [211]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-213">\n        <a href="#cite_note-213">\n         [212]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In an effort to maintain the company\'s unique culture, Google designated a Chief Culture Officer whose purpose was to develop and maintain the culture and work on ways to keep true to the core values that the company was founded on.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CCO_214-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-CCO-214">\n         [213]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google has also faced allegations of\n       <a href="/wiki/Sexism" title="Sexism">\n        sexism\n       </a>\n       and\n       <a href="/wiki/Ageism" title="Ageism">\n        ageism\n       </a>\n       from former employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-215">\n        <a href="#cite_note-215">\n         [214]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-216">\n        <a href="#cite_note-216">\n         [215]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2013, a\n       <a href="/wiki/High-Tech_Employee_Antitrust_Litigation" title="High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation">\n        class action against\n       </a>\n       several\n       <a href="/wiki/Silicon_Valley" title="Silicon Valley">\n        Silicon Valley\n       </a>\n       companies, including Google, was filed for alleged "no cold call" agreements which restrained the recruitment of high-tech employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-217">\n        <a href="#cite_note-217">\n         [216]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Office_locations">\n        Office locations\n        <span id="Office_locations_and_headquarters">\n        </span>\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Further information:\n       <a href="/wiki/Googleplex" title="Googleplex">\n        Googleplex\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2653" data-file-width="3911" decoding="async" height="149" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg/220px-111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg/330px-111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg/440px-111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:111_Eighth_Avenue.jpg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Google\'s New York City office building houses its largest advertising sales team.\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_(cropped).jpg">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1406" data-file-width="3156" decoding="async" height="98" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg/330px-Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg/440px-Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_%28cropped%29.jpg 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Google_at_111_Richmond_Street_West_in_Toronto_(cropped).jpg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Google\'s\n         <a href="/wiki/Toronto" title="Toronto">\n          Toronto\n         </a>\n         office.\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       Google\'s headquarters in\n       <a href="/wiki/Mountain_View,_California" title="Mountain View, California">\n        Mountain View\n       </a>\n       , California is referred to as "the\n       <a href="/wiki/Googleplex" title="Googleplex">\n        Googleplex\n       </a>\n       ", a play on words on the number\n       <a href="/wiki/Googolplex" title="Googolplex">\n        googolplex\n       </a>\n       and the headquarters itself being a\n       <i>\n        complex\n       </i>\n       of buildings. Internationally, Google has over 78 offices in more than 50 countries.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-218">\n        <a href="#cite_note-218">\n         [217]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2006, Google moved into about 300,000 square feet (27,900\xc2\xa0m\n       <sup>\n        2\n       </sup>\n       ) of office space in New York City, at\n       <a href="/wiki/111_Eighth_Avenue" title="111 Eighth Avenue">\n        111 Eighth Avenue\n       </a>\n       in Manhattan. The office was designed and built specially for Google, and houses its largest advertising sales team, which has been instrumental in securing large partnerships.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-219">\n        <a href="#cite_note-219">\n         [218]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2010, Google bought the building housing the headquarter, in a deal that valued the property at around $1.9 billion.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-220">\n        <a href="#cite_note-220">\n         [219]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-221">\n        <a href="#cite_note-221">\n         [220]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In March 2018, Google\'s parent company Alphabet bought the nearby\n       <a href="/wiki/Chelsea_Market" title="Chelsea Market">\n        Chelsea Market\n       </a>\n       building for $2.4 billion. The sale is touted as one of the most expensive real estate transactions for a single building in the history of New York.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-222">\n        <a href="#cite_note-222">\n         [221]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-223">\n        <a href="#cite_note-223">\n         [222]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-224">\n        <a href="#cite_note-224">\n         [223]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-225">\n        <a href="#cite_note-225">\n         [224]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In November 2018, Google announced its plan to expand its New York City office to a capacity of 12,000 employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-226">\n        <a href="#cite_note-226">\n         [225]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The same December, it was announced that a $1 billion, 1,700,000-square-foot (160,000\xc2\xa0m\n       <sup>\n        2\n       </sup>\n       ) headquarters for Google would be built in Manhattan\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/Hudson_Square" title="Hudson Square">\n        Hudson Square\n       </a>\n       neighborhood.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-227">\n        <a href="#cite_note-227">\n         [226]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-228">\n        <a href="#cite_note-228">\n         [227]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Called Google Hudson Square, the new campus is projected to more than double the number of Google employees working in New York City.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-229">\n        <a href="#cite_note-229">\n         [228]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       By late 2006, Google established a new headquarters for its AdWords division in\n       <a href="/wiki/Ann_Arbor,_Michigan" title="Ann Arbor, Michigan">\n        Ann Arbor, Michigan\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-230">\n        <a href="#cite_note-230">\n         [229]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In November 2006, Google opened offices on\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Carnegie_Mellon" title="Carnegie Mellon">\n        Carnegie Mellon\n       </a>\n       \'s campus in\n       <a href="/wiki/Pittsburgh" title="Pittsburgh">\n        Pittsburgh\n       </a>\n       , focusing on shopping-related advertisement coding and\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Smartphone_applications" title="Smartphone applications">\n        smartphone applications\n       </a>\n       and programs.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-231">\n        <a href="#cite_note-231">\n         [230]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-232">\n        <a href="#cite_note-232">\n         [231]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Other office locations in the U.S. include\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Atlanta,_Georgia" title="Atlanta, Georgia">\n        Atlanta, Georgia\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Austin,_Texas" title="Austin, Texas">\n        Austin, Texas\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Boulder,_Colorado" title="Boulder, Colorado">\n        Boulder, Colorado\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">\n        Cambridge, Massachusetts\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco" title="San Francisco">\n        San Francisco\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">\n        California\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Seattle,_Washington" title="Seattle, Washington">\n        Seattle, Washington\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Kirkland,_Washington" title="Kirkland, Washington">\n        Kirkland, Washington\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Birmingham,_Michigan" title="Birmingham, Michigan">\n        Birmingham, Michigan\n       </a>\n       ;\n       <a href="/wiki/Reston,_Virginia" title="Reston, Virginia">\n        Reston, Virginia\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Washington,_D.C." title="Washington, D.C.">\n        Washington, D.C.\n       </a>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-233">\n        <a href="#cite_note-233">\n         [232]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1820" data-file-width="2424" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg/220px-Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg/330px-Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg/440px-Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Google_Headquarters_in_Ireland_Building_Sign.jpg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         Google\'s Dublin Ireland office, headquarters of Google Ads for Europe\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       It also has product research and development operations in cities around the world, namely\n       <a href="/wiki/Sydney" title="Sydney">\n        Sydney\n       </a>\n       (birthplace location of\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_Maps" title="Google Maps">\n        Google Maps\n       </a>\n       )\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-234">\n        <a href="#cite_note-234">\n         [233]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and\n       <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">\n        London\n       </a>\n       (part of\n       <a href="/wiki/Android_(operating_system)" title="Android (operating system)">\n        Android\n       </a>\n       development).\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-235">\n        <a href="#cite_note-235">\n         [234]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In November 2013, Google announced plans for a new\n       <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">\n        London\n       </a>\n       headquarter, a 1 million square foot office able to accommodate 4,500 employees. Recognized as one of the biggest ever commercial property acquisitions at the time of the deal\'s announcement in January,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-236">\n        <a href="#cite_note-236">\n         [235]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google submitted plans for the new headquarter to the\n       <a href="/wiki/Camden_London_Borough_Council" title="Camden London Borough Council">\n        Camden Council\n       </a>\n       in June 2017.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-237">\n        <a href="#cite_note-237">\n         [236]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-238">\n        <a href="#cite_note-238">\n         [237]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In May 2015, Google announced its intention to create its own campus in\n       <a href="/wiki/Hyderabad" title="Hyderabad">\n        Hyderabad\n       </a>\n       , India. The new campus, reported to be the company\'s largest outside the United States, will accommodate 13,000 employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-239">\n        <a href="#cite_note-239">\n         [238]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-240">\n        <a href="#cite_note-240">\n         [239]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Infrastructure">\n        Infrastructure\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Further information:\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_data_centers" title="Google data centers">\n        Google data centers\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_data_centers" title="Google data centers">\n        Google data centers\n       </a>\n       are located in North and South America, Asia, and Europe.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-241">\n        <a href="#cite_note-241">\n         [240]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       There is no official data on the number of\n       <a href="/wiki/Server_(computing)" title="Server (computing)">\n        servers\n       </a>\n       in Google data centers; however, research and advisory firm\n       <a href="/wiki/Gartner" title="Gartner">\n        Gartner\n       </a>\n       estimated in a July 2016 report that Google at the time had 2.5 million servers.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-242">\n        <a href="#cite_note-242">\n         [241]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Traditionally, Google relied on\n       <a href="/wiki/Parallel_computing" title="Parallel computing">\n        parallel computing\n       </a>\n       on commodity hardware like mainstream x86 computers (similar to home PCs) to keep costs per query low.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-243">\n        <a href="#cite_note-243">\n         [242]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-244">\n        <a href="#cite_note-244">\n         [243]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CNET2009_245-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-CNET2009-245">\n         [244]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2005, it started developing its own designs, which were only revealed in 2009.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CNET2009_245-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-CNET2009-245">\n         [244]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In the late 2010s, Google began to build its own private\n       <a href="/wiki/Submarine_communications_cable" title="Submarine communications cable">\n        submarine communications cables\n       </a>\n       . The first, named Curie, connects California with\n       <a href="/wiki/Chile" title="Chile">\n        Chile\n       </a>\n       and is to be completed in 2019.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-246">\n        <a href="#cite_note-246">\n         [245]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The second fully Google-owned undersea cable, named Dunant, connects the United States with France and is planned to begin operation in 2020.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-247">\n        <a href="#cite_note-247">\n         [246]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Environment">\n        Environment\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <p>\n       In October 2006, the company announced plans to install thousands of\n       <a href="/wiki/Solar_panel" title="Solar panel">\n        solar panels\n       </a>\n       to provide up to 1.6\xc2\xa0mega\n       <a href="/wiki/Watt" title="Watt">\n        watts\n       </a>\n       of electricity, enough to satisfy approximately 30% of the campus\' energy needs.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-solar_248-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-solar-248">\n         [247]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The system will be the largest\n       <a href="/wiki/Rooftop_photovoltaic_power_station" title="Rooftop photovoltaic power station">\n        solar power system\n       </a>\n       constructed on a U.S. corporate campus and one of the largest on any corporate site in the world.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-solar_248-1">\n        <a href="#cite_note-solar-248">\n         [247]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Since 2007,\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google has aimed for\n       <a href="/wiki/Carbon_neutrality" title="Carbon neutrality">\n        carbon neutrality\n       </a>\n       in regard to its operations.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-249">\n        <a href="#cite_note-249">\n         [248]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google disclosed in September 2011 that it "continuously uses enough electricity to power 200,000 homes", almost 260 million watts or about a quarter of the output of a nuclear power plant. Total carbon emissions for 2010 were just under 1.5 million metric tons, mostly due to fossil fuels that provide electricity for the data centers. Google said that 25 percent of its energy was supplied by renewable fuels in 2010. An average search uses only 0.3 watt-hours of electricity, so all global searches are only 12.5 million watts or 5% of the total electricity consumption by Google.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-250">\n        <a href="#cite_note-250">\n         [249]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2010,\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google_Energy" title="Google Energy">\n        Google Energy\n       </a>\n       made its first investment in a\n       <a href="/wiki/Renewable_energy" title="Renewable energy">\n        renewable energy\n       </a>\n       project, putting $38.8\xc2\xa0million into two\n       <a href="/wiki/Wind_farm" title="Wind farm">\n        wind farms\n       </a>\n       in\n       <a href="/wiki/North_Dakota" title="North Dakota">\n        North Dakota\n       </a>\n       . The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5\xc2\xa0megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-251">\n        <a href="#cite_note-251">\n         [250]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In February 2010, the\n       <a href="/wiki/Federal_Energy_Regulatory_Commission" title="Federal Energy Regulatory Commission">\n        Federal Energy Regulatory Commission\n       </a>\n       FERC granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-252">\n        <a href="#cite_note-252">\n         [251]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-253">\n        <a href="#cite_note-253">\n         [252]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In July 2010, Google signed an agreement with an Iowa wind farm to buy 114 megawatts of energy for 20 years.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-wind_energy_254-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-wind_energy-254">\n         [253]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In December 2016, Google announced that\xe2\x80\x94starting in 2017\xe2\x80\x94it will power all of its data centers, as well as all of its offices, from 100% renewable energy. The commitment will make Google "the world\'s largest corporate buyer of renewable power, with commitments reaching 2.6 gigawatts (2,600 megawatts) of wind and solar energy". Google also stated that it does not count that as its final goal; it says that "since the wind doesn\'t blow 24 hours a day, we\'ll also broaden our purchases to a variety of energy sources that can enable renewable power, every hour of every day". Additionally, the project will "help support communities" around the world, as the purchase commitments will "result in infrastructure investments of more than $3.5 billion globally", and will "generate tens of millions of dollars per year in revenue to local property owners, and tens of millions more to local and national governments in tax revenue".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-255">\n        <a href="#cite_note-255">\n         [254]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-256">\n        <a href="#cite_note-256">\n         [255]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-257">\n        <a href="#cite_note-257">\n         [256]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In November 2017, Google bought 536 megawatts of wind power. The purchase made the firm reach 100% renewable energy. The wind energy comes from two power plants in South Dakota, one in Iowa and one in Oklahoma.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-258">\n        <a href="#cite_note-258">\n         [257]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In September 2019, Google\'s chief executive announced plans for a $2 billion wind and solar investment, the biggest renewable energy deal in corporate history. This will grow their green energy profile by 40%, giving them an extra 1.6 gigawatt of clean energy, the company said.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-259">\n        <a href="#cite_note-259">\n         [258]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google donates to politicians who deny climate change including\n       <a href="/wiki/Jim_Inhofe" title="Jim Inhofe">\n        Jim Inhofe\n       </a>\n       as well as sponsoring climate change denial political groups including the\n       <a href="/wiki/State_Policy_Network" title="State Policy Network">\n        State Policy Network\n       </a>\n       and the\n       <a href="/wiki/Competitive_Enterprise_Institute" title="Competitive Enterprise Institute">\n        Competitive Enterprise Institute\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-260">\n        <a href="#cite_note-260">\n         [259]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-261">\n        <a href="#cite_note-261">\n         [260]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-262">\n        <a href="#cite_note-262">\n         [261]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Philanthropy">\n        Philanthropy\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Main article:\n       <a href="/wiki/Google.org" title="Google.org">\n        Google.org\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       In 2004, Google formed the not-for-profit philanthropic\n       <a href="/wiki/Google.org" title="Google.org">\n        Google.org\n       </a>\n       , with a start-up fund of $1\xc2\xa0billion.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-philanthropy_263-0">\n        <a href="#cite_note-philanthropy-263">\n         [262]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The mission of the organization is to create awareness about\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Climate_change" title="Climate change">\n        climate change\n       </a>\n       , global public health, and global poverty. One of its first projects was to develop a viable\n       <a href="/wiki/Plug-in_hybrid" title="Plug-in hybrid">\n        plug-in hybrid\n       </a>\n       <a href="/wiki/Electric_vehicle" title="Electric vehicle">\n        electric vehicle\n       </a>\n       that can attain 100 miles per gallon. Google hired\n       <a href="/wiki/Larry_Brilliant" title="Larry Brilliant">\n        Larry Brilliant\n       </a>\n       as the program\'s executive director in 2004\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-264">\n        <a href="#cite_note-264">\n         [263]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and Megan Smith has since\n       <sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;">\n        <a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Google&amp;action=edit">\n         [update]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       replaced him as director.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-265">\n        <a href="#cite_note-265">\n         [264]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In 2008, Google announced its "project 10\n       <sup>\n        100\n       </sup>\n       " which accepted ideas for how to help the community and then allowed Google users to vote on their favorites.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-266">\n        <a href="#cite_note-266">\n         [265]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       After two years of silence, during which many wondered what had happened to the program,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-267">\n        <a href="#cite_note-267">\n         [266]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Google revealed the winners of the project, giving a total of ten million dollars to various ideas ranging from non-profit organizations that promote education to a website that intends to make all legal documents public and online.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-268">\n        <a href="#cite_note-268">\n         [267]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In March 2007, in partnership with the\n       <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_Sciences_Research_Institute" title="Mathematical Sciences Research Institute">\n        Mathematical Sciences Research Institute\n       </a>\n       (MSRI), Google hosted the first\n       <a href="/wiki/Julia_Robinson_Mathematics_Festival" title="Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival">\n        Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival\n       </a>\n       at its headquarters in Mountain View.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-269">\n        <a href="#cite_note-269">\n         [268]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In 2011, Google donated 1\xc2\xa0million euros to\n       <a href="/wiki/International_Mathematical_Olympiad" title="International Mathematical Olympiad">\n        International Mathematical Olympiad\n       </a>\n       to support the next five annual International Mathematical Olympiads (2011\xe2\x80\x932015).\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-270">\n        <a href="#cite_note-270">\n         [269]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-271">\n        <a href="#cite_note-271">\n         [270]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In July 2012, Google launched a "\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Legalize_Love" title="Legalize Love">\n        Legalize Love\n       </a>\n       " campaign in support of\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Gay_rights" title="Gay rights">\n        gay rights\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-272">\n        <a href="#cite_note-272">\n         [271]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h2>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Criticism_and_controversy">\n        Criticism and controversy\n       </span>\n      </h2>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Main articles:\n       <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Google" title="Criticism of Google">\n        Criticism of Google\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Censorship_by_Google" title="Censorship by Google">\n        Censorship by Google\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Privacy_concerns_regarding_Google" title="Privacy concerns regarding Google">\n        Privacy concerns regarding Google\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <table class="box-Summarize plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style" role="presentation">\n       <tbody>\n        <tr>\n         <td class="mbox-image">\n          <div style="width:52px">\n           <img alt="" data-file-height="48" data-file-width="48" decoding="async" height="40" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/60px-Edit-clear.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/80px-Edit-clear.svg.png 2x" width="40"/>\n          </div>\n         </td>\n         <td class="mbox-text">\n          <div class="mbox-text-span">\n           <b>\n            This section should include a better summary of\n            <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Google" title="Criticism of Google">\n             Criticism of Google\n            </a>\n            .\n           </b>\n           See\n           <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Summary_style" title="Wikipedia:Summary style">\n            Wikipedia:Summary style\n           </a>\n           for information on how to properly incorporate it into this article\'s main text.\n           <small class="date-container">\n            <i>\n             (\n             <span class="date">\n              April 2019\n             </span>\n             )\n            </i>\n           </small>\n          </div>\n         </td>\n        </tr>\n       </tbody>\n      </table>\n      <div class="thumb tright">\n       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">\n        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Google_bus_protest.jpg">\n         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2142" data-file-width="3000" decoding="async" height="157" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Google_bus_protest.jpg/220px-Google_bus_protest.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Google_bus_protest.jpg/330px-Google_bus_protest.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/Google_bus_protest.jpg/440px-Google_bus_protest.jpg 2x" width="220"/>\n        </a>\n        <div class="thumbcaption">\n         <div class="magnify">\n          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Google_bus_protest.jpg" title="Enlarge">\n          </a>\n         </div>\n         San Francisco activists\n         <a href="/wiki/San_Francisco_tech_bus_protests" title="San Francisco tech bus protests">\n          protest privately owned shuttle buses\n         </a>\n         that transport workers for tech companies such as Google from their homes in San Francisco and Oakland to corporate campuses in Silicon Valley.\n        </div>\n       </div>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       Google\'s market dominance has led to prominent media coverage, including\n       <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Google" title="Criticism of Google">\n        criticism of the company\n       </a>\n       over issues such as\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google_tax_avoidance" title="Google tax avoidance">\n        aggressive tax avoidance\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-273">\n        <a href="#cite_note-273">\n         [272]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Google#Page_rank" title="Criticism of Google">\n        search neutrality\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Google#Copyright_issues" title="Criticism of Google">\n        copyright\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Censorship_by_Google" title="Censorship by Google">\n        censorship\n       </a>\n       of search results and content,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-274">\n        <a href="#cite_note-274">\n         [273]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       and\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Google_privacy" title="Google privacy">\n        privacy\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-275">\n        <a href="#cite_note-275">\n         [274]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-276">\n        <a href="#cite_note-276">\n         [275]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Other criticisms include alleged misuse and manipulation of search results, its use of others\'\n       <a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" title="Intellectual property">\n        intellectual property\n       </a>\n       , concerns that its\n       <a href="/wiki/Data_collection" title="Data collection">\n        compilation of data\n       </a>\n       may violate people\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/Internet_privacy" title="Internet privacy">\n        privacy\n       </a>\n       , and the\n       <a href="/wiki/Energy_consumption" title="Energy consumption">\n        energy consumption\n       </a>\n       of its servers, as well as concerns over traditional business issues such as\n       <a href="/wiki/Monopoly" title="Monopoly">\n        monopoly\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Restraint_of_trade" title="Restraint of trade">\n        restraint of trade\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <a href="/wiki/Anti-competitive_practices" title="Anti-competitive practices">\n        anti-competitive practices\n       </a>\n       , and\n       <a href="/wiki/Patent_infringement" title="Patent infringement">\n        patent infringement\n       </a>\n       .\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google formerly adhered to the\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Internet_censorship_in_the_People%27s_Republic_of_China" title="Internet censorship in the People\'s Republic of China">\n        Internet censorship policies of China\n       </a>\n       ,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-277">\n        <a href="#cite_note-277">\n         [276]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       enforced by means of filters colloquially known as "The\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Great_Firewall_of_China" title="Great Firewall of China">\n        Great Firewall of China\n       </a>\n       ", but\n       <a href="/wiki/Censorship_by_Google#China" title="Censorship by Google">\n        no longer does so\n       </a>\n       . As a result, all Google services except for Chinese Google Maps are blocked from access within mainland China without the aid of VPNs, proxy servers, or other similar technologies.\n       <i>\n        The Intercept\n       </i>\n       reported in August 2018 that Google is developing for the People\'s Republic of China a censored version of its search engine (known as\n       <a href="/wiki/Dragonfly_(search_engine)" title="Dragonfly (search engine)">\n        Dragonfly\n       </a>\n       ) "that will blacklist websites and search terms about human rights, democracy, religion, and peaceful protest".\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-278">\n        <a href="#cite_note-278">\n         [277]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-279">\n        <a href="#cite_note-279">\n         [278]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       However, the project had been withheld due to privacy concerns.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-280">\n        <a href="#cite_note-280">\n         [279]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Following media reports about\n       <a href="/wiki/PRISM_(surveillance_program)" title="PRISM (surveillance program)">\n        PRISM\n       </a>\n       , NSA\'s massive electronic\n       <a href="/wiki/Mass_surveillance" title="Mass surveillance">\n        surveillance program\n       </a>\n       , in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Google.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-281">\n        <a href="#cite_note-281">\n         [280]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       According to leaks of said program, Google joined the PRISM program in 2009.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-282">\n        <a href="#cite_note-282">\n         [281]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Google has worked with the\n       <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Defense" title="United States Department of Defense">\n        United States Department of Defense\n       </a>\n       on drone software through the 2017 "Project Maven" that could be used to improve the accuracy of\n       <a href="/wiki/Drone_strike" title="Drone strike">\n        drone strikes\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-283">\n        <a href="#cite_note-283">\n         [282]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Thousands of Google employees, including senior engineers, have signed a letter urging Google CEO\n       <a href="/wiki/Sundar_Pichai" title="Sundar Pichai">\n        Sundar Pichai\n       </a>\n       to end a controversial contract with the Pentagon.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-284">\n        <a href="#cite_note-284">\n         [283]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       In response to the backlash, Google ultimately decided to not renew their DoD contract, set to expire in 2019.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-285">\n        <a href="#cite_note-285">\n         [284]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       Shona Ghosh, a journalist for\n       <a href="/wiki/Business_Insider" title="Business Insider">\n        Business Insider\n       </a>\n       , noted that an increasing digital\n       <a href="/wiki/Resistance_movement" title="Resistance movement">\n        resistance movement\n       </a>\n       against Google has grown. A major hub for critics of Google in order to organize to abstain from using Google products is the\n       <a href="/wiki/Reddit" title="Reddit">\n        Reddit\n       </a>\n       page for the\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Subreddit" title="Subreddit">\n        subreddit\n       </a>\n       /r/degoogle.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-286">\n        <a href="#cite_note-286">\n         [285]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In July 2018, Mozilla Program Manager Chris Peterson accused Google of intentionally slowing down YouTube performance on Firefox.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-287">\n        <a href="#cite_note-287">\n         [286]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In April 2019 former\n       <a href="/wiki/Mozilla" title="Mozilla">\n        Mozilla\n       </a>\n       executive Jonathan Nightingale accused Google of intentionally and systematically sabotaging the\n       <a href="/wiki/Firefox" title="Firefox">\n        Firefox\n       </a>\n       browser over the past decade in order to boost\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_Chrome" title="Google Chrome">\n        Chrome\'s\n       </a>\n       adoption.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-288">\n        <a href="#cite_note-288">\n         [287]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       In November 2019, the Office for Civil Rights of the\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Department_of_Health_and_Human_Services" title="Department of Health and Human Services">\n        Department of Health and Human Services\n       </a>\n       began investigation into\n       <a href="/wiki/Project_Nightingale" title="Project Nightingale">\n        Project Nightingale\n       </a>\n       , to assess whether the "mass collection of individuals\xe2\x80\x99 medical records" complied with\n       <a href="/wiki/Health_Insurance_Portability_and_Accountability_Act" title="Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act">\n        HIPPA\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-289">\n        <a href="#cite_note-289">\n         [288]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       According to\n       <i>\n        The Wall Street Journal\n       </i>\n       , Google commenced the project in secret, in 2018, with\n       <a href="/wiki/St._Louis" title="St. Louis">\n        St. Louis\n       </a>\n       -based\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Healthcare" title="Healthcare">\n        healthcare\n       </a>\n       company\n       <a class="new" href="/w/index.php?title=Ascension_(company)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" title="Ascension (company) (page does not exist)">\n        Ascension\n       </a>\n       .\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-290">\n        <a href="#cite_note-290">\n         [289]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <h3>\n       <span class="mw-headline" id="Litigation">\n        Litigation\n       </span>\n      </h3>\n      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">\n       Main article:\n       <a href="/wiki/Google_litigation" title="Google litigation">\n        Google litigation\n       </a>\n      </div>\n      <p>\n       Google has been involved in a number of lawsuits including the\n       <a href="/wiki/High-Tech_Employee_Antitrust_Litigation" title="High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation">\n        High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation\n       </a>\n       which resulted in Google being one of four companies to pay a $415 million settlement to employees.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-291">\n        <a href="#cite_note-291">\n         [290]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       On June 27, 2017, the company received a record fine of\n       <a href="/wiki/Euro" title="Euro">\n        \xe2\x82\xac\n       </a>\n       2.42 billion from the\n       <a href="/wiki/European_Union" title="European Union">\n        European Union\n       </a>\n       for "promoting its own shopping comparison service at the top of search results."\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-292">\n        <a href="#cite_note-292">\n         [291]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       Commenting on the penalty,\n       <i>\n        <a href="/wiki/New_Scientist" title="New Scientist">\n         New Scientist\n        </a>\n       </i>\n       magazine said: "The hefty sum \xe2\x80\x93 the largest ever doled out by the EU\'s competition regulators \xe2\x80\x93 will sting in the short term, but Google can handle it. Alphabet, Google\xe2\x80\x99s parent company, made a profit of $2.5 billion (\xe2\x82\xac2.2 billion) in the first six weeks of 2017 alone. The real impact of the ruling is that Google must stop using its dominance as a search engine to give itself the edge in another market: online price comparisons." The company disputed the ruling.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-293">\n        <a href="#cite_note-293">\n         [292]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       The hearing at the General Court of Luxembourg was scheduled for 2020. The court is going to deliver the ultimate judgment by the end of the year.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-294">\n        <a href="#cite_note-294">\n         [293]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       On July 18, 2018,\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-295">\n        <a href="#cite_note-295">\n         [294]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       the\n       <a href="/wiki/European_Commissioner_for_Competition" title="European Commissioner for Competition">\n        European Commission\n       </a>\n       fined Google \xe2\x82\xac4.34 billion for breaching EU antitrust rules. The abuse of dominant position has been referred to Google\'s constraint applied on Android device manufacturers and network operators to ensure that traffic on Android devices goes to the Google search engine. On October 9, 2018, Google confirmed\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-296">\n        <a href="#cite_note-296">\n         [295]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       that it had appealed the fine to the\n       <a href="/wiki/General_Court_(European_Union)" title="General Court (European Union)">\n        General Court\n       </a>\n       of the European Union.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-297">\n        <a href="#cite_note-297">\n         [296]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       On January 21, 2019, French data regulator\n       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/CNIL" title="CNIL">\n        CNIL\n       </a>\n       imposed a record \xe2\x82\xac50 million fine on Google for breaching the European Union\'s\n       <a href="/wiki/General_Data_Protection_Regulation" title="General Data Protection Regulation">\n        General Data Protection Regulation\n       </a>\n       . The judgment claimed Google had failed to sufficiently inform users of its methods for collecting data to personalize advertising. Google issued a statement saying it was \xe2\x80\x9cdeeply committed\xe2\x80\x9d to transparency and was \xe2\x80\x9cstudying the decision\xe2\x80\x9d before determining its response.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-298">\n        <a href="#cite_note-298">\n         [297]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n      </p>\n      <p>\n       On March 20, 2019, the European Commission imposed a \xe2\x82\xac1.49 billion ($1.69 billion) fine on Google for preventing rivals from being able to \xe2\x80\x9ccompete and innovate fairly\xe2\x80\x9d in the online advertising market.\n       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-299">\n        <a href="#cite_note-299">\n         [298]\n        </a>\n       </sup>\n       European Union competition commissioner Margrethe Vestager said Google had violated EU antitrust rules by \xe2\x80\x9cimposing anti-competitive contractual restrictions on third-party websites\xe2\x80\x9d that required them to exclude search results from Google\'s rivals.
